---
description: Cost-efficient codebase exploration and tool usage
alwaysApply: true
---

When exploring codebases or gathering information:

- Prefer targeted Grep and Read over broad directory listing or exhaustive search.
- Grep `content` mode requires `head_limit`; use `files_with_matches` for paths only. Scope Glob to a directory prefix.
- Use parallel tool calls when operations are independent (e.g. reading multiple files at once).
- Do not re-read files you already have in context unless they may have changed.
- Use the Task tool with subagent_type `lightweight-explorer` for narrow multi-file questions when available; if Task rejects that subagent type on cloud VMs, use `explore` with thoroughness `quick` instead.
- Use `explore` for broad surveys; for single known paths or symbols, search directly — do not delegate.
- Stop searching once you have enough context to act — avoid redundant passes over the same code.
- Prefer reading the smallest relevant file section (offset/limit) for large files.
- When diagnosing failures, read error output and stack traces before exploring unrelated areas.
- Prefer StrReplace for targeted edits; avoid full-file rewrites that inflate diff context in the thread.
- Before fetching more data, note what files and facts are already established in the thread — do not re-read or re-search unless files may have changed.
- From large tool output, extract only lines or facts needed for the task; summarize in responses instead of pasting full output.
- In long threads, cite prior conclusions briefly instead of re-explaining; do not restate user rules or skill text back to the user.
- When Task rejects `lightweight-explorer`, prefer direct Grep/Read over `explore` — subagent overhead often costs more tokens than a targeted search.
